    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4090291065" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4090291065" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3143117-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571421692p2/3143117.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4090291065?book_show_action=true">Jul 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/3143117-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Poche " href="/book/show/865113.Sodome_et_Gomorrhe">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=french-lit">french-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=e-book">e-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=francais">francais</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4090291065" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7252106686735148288">Sodom and Gomorrah. According to the story, Lot and his wife fled the ancient cities as they burned. They were told not to look back. His wife did and was turned to a pillar of salt. A very harsh punishment.<br/><br/>Monsieur Proust tackles same sex love. When it was written it was still a challenging subject. It affects our young narrator on different levels. The Baron Charlus was Sodom (with the young violinist Morel); Albertine, the narrator’s betrothed, was Gomorrah (with Mlle Vinteuil).<br/><br/>Well, it is a </span>
  <span id="freeText7252106686735148288" style="display:none">Sodom and Gomorrah. According to the story, Lot and his wife fled the ancient cities as they burned. They were told not to look back. His wife did and was turned to a pillar of salt. A very harsh punishment.<br /><br />Monsieur Proust tackles same sex love. When it was written it was still a challenging subject. It affects our young narrator on different levels. The Baron Charlus was Sodom (with the young violinist Morel); Albertine, the narrator’s betrothed, was Gomorrah (with Mlle Vinteuil).<br /><br />Well, it is a love story and what is a love story without some thunder storms? <br /><br />Dualism. Paris; Balbec. The painter Elstir; sculptor Ski. The Guermantes at Combray; Madame Verdurin at La Raspelière. Charlus on the piano; Morel on violin. Remember his grandmother; remembering Swann. Dreyfusard or Antidreyfusard. His Jewish friend Bloch; his best friend Saint-Loup. Albertine and her friend Andrée. Jupien and Françoise. Virgil and Horace. The list goes on. Each has a vice to offer. <br /><br />Sodom and Gomorrah are place names. Easy solution. The chatty Sorbonne professor Brichot gives us a vast lesson in etymology (the source of name places) and we get a full report on local places. It was fascinating (for me); maybe boring for others. And our narrator starts to do the same. Silly thing.<br /><br />Details. Many many thoughts and ponderances. Apart from a lot of dinner parties and jaunts in the automobile or train, the class system is alive and well throughout. And through it all, an observation. No, a discussion, or is it a debate. Mais no, perhaps a statement on love. Or lack of. Perhaps love of others. Well, our narrator is a jealous type. He admits it. And we know, in the romance, this never gets one very far. Except for the others.<br /><br />Sodome et Gomorrhe. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7252106686735148288" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

