    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3868060998" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3868060998" />
    <a title="Michelle Curie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27203016-michelle-curie"><img alt="Michelle Curie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620301438p2/27203016.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3868060998?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle Curie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle Curie" href="/user/show/27203016-michelle-curie">Michelle Curie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27203016-michelle-curie?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3868060998" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11585918661223934378">Having read <i>Sodom and Gomorrah</i> means I&apos;m more than halfway through Proust&apos;s entire <i>In Search of Lost Time</i>. For those having clocked in some Bible study down the road it will come to no surprise that this volume deals a lot with homosexuality, both male and female. <br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1617432441i/31124308._SX540_.png' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>We&apos;re all well aware by now that Proust and his narrator both like to ponder and the events here give him reason to think about how sexuality developed, how biological drives play into social interaction and what hopes and desires come</span>
  <span id="freeText11585918661223934378" style="display:none">Having read <i>Sodom and Gomorrah</i> means I'm more than halfway through Proust's entire <i>In Search of Lost Time</i>. For those having clocked in some Bible study down the road it will come to no surprise that this volume deals a lot with homosexuality, both male and female. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1617432441i/31124308._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>We're all well aware by now that Proust and his narrator both like to ponder and the events here give him reason to think about how sexuality developed, how biological drives play into social interaction and what hopes and desires come with that. <br><br>After having felt exhausted after <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3746967511" rel="nofollow noopener">(one might say bored)</a> by the preceding events, or lack thereof, the opening sequence here caught my interest once more. The narrator watches Monsieur de Charlus as he flirts with a tailor, noticing how their bodies show signs of attraction, despite their different social status and suddenly so many past encounters start to make sense to him. What's captivating about this scene is less what's happening though, and more how Proust set it up. He weaves the observations into the narrative of how bees pollinate flowers, giving everything a sensuality that underlines how sexuality is expressed <i>everywhere</i>. <br><br><b>This is also the volume that ties the threads of Proust's world together.</b> There's less daydreaming, less drifting off. Maybe it's a sign of Marcel's ageing, his growing up. We're familiar with most of the characters appearing here, the places are by now known by us. It's satisfying to witness and feels a bit like a picture, that was blurry before, is now slowly getting sharper. <br><br><b>Beware that his treatment of homosexuality is showing signs of the time.</b> While there's something very forward in Marcel's realisation and acceptance of sexuality in all forms being omnipresent, there <i>are</i> homophobic doubts expressed, which most likely reflect the author's own struggles. While this might be regrettable, any other portrayal would seem absurd considering the times that Proust lived in. Take it or leave it. <br><br><b>I think I'm coming to my own acceptance of Proust.</b> My feelings while reading his work often resemble a rollercoaster ride emotionally – I'm constantly torn between hanging onto every word and wondering what the point of all this rambling really is. Part of my reading journey has, by accident, become dedicated to the attempt of figuring out <i>why</i> I'm reading hundreds of pages of mundane conversations irrelevant to me. Honestly, I have no idea, but maybe that's part of the charm of reading itself. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11585918661223934378" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


